paragraphs.title: Using Zeppelin for Graphing and Filtering
paragraphs.text:
%md
<link rel="stylesheet" href="https://doc.splicemachine.com/zeppelin/css/zepstyles2.css" />

# Using Zeppelin for Graphing and Filtering

This notebook introduces you to the graphing and filtering capabilities of Zeppelin, which allow you to easily visualize query results in various formats.

In this notebook, we'll query the TPCH data, looking at specific supplier nations, and looking for specific account balances; we'll display our results in different graphic formats to illustrate how useful the Zeppelin visualization tools can be. We'll:

1. *Simplify Query 2, adding two additional filters and a default value*. This allows us to change the values directly in the input fields instead of editing the queries.
2. *Run the query "as-is".*
3. *Change the `nationName` in the input box from `FRANCE` to `ROMANIA` and display the results in several different formats*, so you can see some of the power of Zeppelin visualizations.

Using Zeppelin for Graphing and Filtering

This notebook introduces you to the graphing and filtering capabilities of Zeppelin, which allow you to easily visualize query results in various formats.

In this notebook, we’ll query the TPCH data, looking at specific supplier nations, and looking for specific account balances; we’ll display our results in different graphic formats to illustrate how useful the Zeppelin visualization tools can be. We’ll:

  1. Simplify Query 2, adding two additional filters and a default value. This allows us to change the values directly in the input fields instead of editing the queries.
  2. Run the query “as-is”.
  3. Change the nationName in the input box from FRANCE to ROMANIA and display the results in several different formats, so you can see some of the power of Zeppelin visualizations.

paragraphs.text:
%splicemachine
select
	s_acctbal as Balance,
    s_name as Supplier
from
	TPCH1.supplier,
	TPCH1.nation
where
	s_nationkey = n_nationkey
	and n_name = ${nationName='FRANCE'}
	and s_acctbal < ${balanceThreshold=0} 
order by
	s_acctbal desc
{limit 100}
